                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="18"
                        FontWeight="SemiBold"
                        Text="Observability — Metrics · Logs · Traces" />
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>Three pillars of observability are covered by the same open-source stack used locally, now running inside the internet-bank Kubernetes namespace alongside the application.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>Metrics: Prometheus v3 scrapes the api and postgres-exporter every 15 seconds. Custom application metrics track request counts, computation latency, and Redis cache hit/miss ratios per operation. Grafana visualises these with pre-provisioned dashboards.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>Logs: Promtail runs as a DaemonSet, reading container logs from the Docker socket on each node and forwarding structured JSON to Loki. Log lines are queryable in Grafana using LogQL, correlated with traces via the trace ID injected into every log entry by the OTel agent.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>Traces: The OTel Java agent auto-instruments all HTTP requests, JDBC calls, and Redis operations. Spans are sent to Tempo over OTLP/gRPC. From Grafana you can jump from a slow request in a dashboard directly to its full distributed trace.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <!--  Infrastructure & Scaling  -->
            <Border
                Padding="28"
                Background="White"
                BorderBrush="#E0E0E0"
                BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="12">
                <Border.Shadow>
                    <ThemeShadow />
                </Border.Shadow>
                <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="18"
                        FontWeight="SemiBold"
                        Text="Infrastructure &amp; Auto-Scaling" />
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>The application runs in an Amazon EKS cluster in eu-central-1 (Frankfurt), inside a dedicated internet-bank namespace. Container images are stored in a private Amazon ECR repository.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>Both the api and web-client Deployments start with three replicas and are covered by a HorizontalPodAutoscaler (HPA). The api HPA scales between 3 and 10 pods, targeting 70% CPU; scale-up adds two pods per minute and scale-down removes one pod per minute with a 5-minute stabilisation window to avoid flapping. The web-client HPA uses the same CPU threshold plus an 80% memory target.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>PodDisruptionBudgets ensure at least two replicas of each service remain available during voluntary disruptions such as node drains or rolling updates. A NetworkPolicy restricts pod-to-pod traffic to only the paths required by the application.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <!--  CI/CD  -->
            <Border
                Padding="28"
                Background="White"
                BorderBrush="#E0E0E0"
                BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="12">
                <Border.Shadow>
                    <ThemeShadow />
                </Border.Shadow>
                <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="18"
                        FontWeight="SemiBold"
                        Text="CI/CD — GitHub Actions" />
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>Every push to the master branch triggers the CI/CD pipeline. The workflow builds the Uno WASM client with dotnet publish, runs the Spring Boot API build with Maven inside a multi-stage Docker build (compile → download OTel agent → JRE runtime image), and pushes both container images to ECR tagged as :latest.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="14"
                        Foreground="#333333"
                        LineHeight="22"
                        TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run>The pipeline then authenticates to the EKS cluster and issues a rolling update by patching the image on both Deployments. EKS performs the rollout gradually — new pods start, liveness and readiness probes pass, then old pods are terminated — keeping the application live throughout the deploy.</Run>
                    </TextBlock>
