            <!--  Future Improvements  -->
            <Border
                Padding="28"
                Background="White"
                BorderBrush="#E0E0E0"
                BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="12">
                <Border.Shadow>
                    <ThemeShadow />
                </Border.Shadow>
                <StackPanel Spacing="20">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="18"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Text="Future Improvements" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="13"
                            Foreground="#777777"
                            Text="The next meaningful steps to make this a production-grade AWS deployment."
                            TextWrapping="Wrap" />
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  RDS  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="Replace the PostgreSQL StatefulSet with Amazon RDS" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>Running PostgreSQL as a Kubernetes StatefulSet requires the cluster to manage storage provisioning, WAL archiving, point-in-time recovery, and replication manually. Amazon RDS (or Aurora PostgreSQL) takes ownership of all of that — automated backups, multi-AZ standby failover, minor version patching, and storage auto-scaling — and exposes a standard PostgreSQL endpoint. The application code and Spring Data JPA configuration are unchanged; only the DB_HOST environment variable in the k8s Secret needs updating. This change removes an entire category of operational risk from the cluster and is the expected pattern for any serious AWS workload.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  ElastiCache  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="Replace the Redis Deployment with Amazon ElastiCache" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>The current Redis Deployment is ephemeral by design — a pod restart simply warms the cache from scratch. ElastiCache for Redis adds a managed replication group with automatic failover: if the primary node fails, ElastiCache promotes a read replica within seconds with no application restart required. It also provides cluster-mode sharding for horizontal scale, built-in encryption in transit and at rest, and CloudWatch metrics out of the box. As with RDS, the only application change is a different REDIS_HOST value; the Lettuce client and Spring Data Redis configuration remain untouched.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <!--  Design Decisions  -->
            <Border
                Padding="28"
                Background="White"
                BorderBrush="#E0E0E0"
                BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="12">
                <Border.Shadow>
                    <ThemeShadow />
                </Border.Shadow>
                <StackPanel Spacing="20">
                    <TextBlock
                        FontSize="18"
                        FontWeight="SemiBold"
                        Text="Design Decisions" />

                    <!--  Decision 1  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="Redis + Server-Sent Events for primes, not a plain HTTP response" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>Computing all primes up to 10,000 is fast, but streaming SSE lets the client start rendering results before the sieve is complete, making the UI feel responsive regardless of server load. Caching the per-limit result set in Redis means the second request for any limit costs one cache read and zero CPU — the API pod is free to handle other work immediately. This combination makes the endpoint both low-latency and horizontally scalable: any replica can serve any cached result.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  Decision 2  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="Java 21 virtual threads instead of reactive programming" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>Project Loom virtual threads (enabled with spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true) give the throughput benefits of non-blocking I/O while keeping the familiar thread-per-request programming model. The codebase reads as plain blocking Java — no reactive chains, no callback hell — yet the JVM schedules thousands of in-flight requests on a small carrier-thread pool. This was a deliberate trade-off: maintainability and debuggability over the marginal performance gains of a fully reactive stack for this workload.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  Decision 3  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="StatefulSet for PostgreSQL, Deployment for Redis" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>PostgreSQL requires a stable network identity and a persistent volume that survives pod restarts — exactly what a StatefulSet provides. Redis is used purely as an ephemeral cache: if the pod restarts, the cache is cold but correct. Running it as a plain Deployment keeps the configuration simpler and avoids the overhead of persistent storage for data that intentionally has a 24-hour TTL anyway.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  Decision 4  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="AWS ALB Ingress Controller over nginx ingress" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>The AWS Load Balancer Controller provisions a native Application Load Balancer per Ingress object. This means TLS termination, certificate rotation (via ACM), HTTP → HTTPS redirect, and layer-7 routing are all handled outside the cluster without an extra nginx ingress pod that would itself need HA. The ALB targets pods directly by IP (target-type: ip), bypassing kube-proxy for one fewer network hop on every request.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  Decision 5  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="OTel zero-code Java agent instead of manual instrumentation" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>The OTel Java agent attaches at JVM startup via -javaagent and instruments Spring MVC, JDBC, HikariCP, and Lettuce (Redis) automatically. This gives complete distributed traces — including database query spans and Redis round-trip times — with zero changes to application code. It also injects a trace ID into every log entry, enabling one-click correlation from a log line in Grafana to the full request trace in Tempo.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

                    <!--  Decision 6  -->
                    <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            FontWeight="SemiBold"
                            Foreground="#1A1A1A"
                            Text="Uno Platform WASM for the frontend" />
                        <TextBlock
                            FontSize="14"
                            Foreground="#333333"
                            LineHeight="22"
                            TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            <Run>Uno Platform compiles a single C# / XAML codebase to WebAssembly, Android, iOS, macOS, Linux and Windows. Using WASM for this case study demonstrates that the same application logic and UI code can target the browser without JavaScript, and that a .NET developer can produce a deployable web frontend without switching language or framework. The Skia rendering backend ensures pixel-identical output across all platforms.</Run>
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>

